Perfect Vision will work with any standard NTSC video signal.  Some examples would be the video out from a VCR, color or black and white video camera, or a TV.  Perfect Vision throws away all of the color signal (if there is any) when it digitizes.  Therefore, a color camera is used in exactly the same way that a black and white one is.

The Perfect Vision has a phono (RCA) type video input.  You should use a shielded RCA patch cord to connect your video signal to the Perfect Vision.  Not all video sources use an RCA jack for the video out; however, converters are cheap and easy to find (try your local Radio Shack.)

The quality of your digitized picture is directly related to the quality of your video source.  Sources that are free of noise will result in clearer pictures.  Also, not all video signals have the same resolution.  For example, black and white cameras generally have a higher bandwith than color cameras, and thus give better quality results.  Also, cameras give much better video quality than home VCRs.  This is because the "bandwidth" of the VCR is much lower than a camera's.

Note that the popular Panasonic B/W camera, model # WV-1410 works fine with Perfect Vision.  Although we don't specifically recommend this camera, it is popular, cheap, and works just fine with Perfect Vision.


SÅeÅtÅtÅiÅnÅgÅ ÅBÅrÅiÅgÅhÅtÅnÅeÅsÅsÅ ÅaÅnÅdÅ ÅCÅoÅnÅtÅrÅaÅsÅtÅ


The quality of your digitized pictures is directly related to how you adjust the two knobs on the front of your digitizer, "Brightness" and "Contrast".  You should carefully adjust these before doing any serious digitizing.  The following is a step-by-step system to set the knobs.

HINT: For those who are using a camera as an input source, first connect your camera directly to a monitor that accepts a composite video signal (if you have one) and focus it on the object (picture, person, etc.) you want to digitize.  It is possible to focus your camera while using Perfect Vision; it's just a big pain. Of course, VCRs and laserdisks don't need focusing.  Remember also that some monitors switch between video input and other kinds.  The switch that controls this input selection must be set to "composite video" to work correctly with your video source.

Now, connect your digitizer and turn it on.  Turn on your PC and run the Perfect Vision program.  You should see a large list of options available to you.  Check that the correct graphics card is selected (it should do this automatically) and the correct printer port is selected.  See appendix C for more about printer ports.

Now press the F8 key.  A blank screen with a short list of commands  at the bottom should appear.  Press the "c" key.

At this point, digitized pictures should start to appear on your screen at about one every five seconds.  If they do not, make sure that you have a video source hooked up to your Perfect Vision, that your Perfect Vision is turned on, and that you followed the steps outlined previously in the section "Hooking up the Hardware."  If the screen is totally black or white, but no flashing cursors or error messages appear, then your Perfect Vision knobs are just badly adjusted.

If, when you press the "c" key to digitize, a blinking cursor appears or an error message appears, you can get back to the digitizing menu by pressing the space bar.  There will be a delay of 1-10 seconds before you actually see the menu again, though, so don't immediately assume it has crashed.

When your digitizer is definitely working, turn both knobs all the way clockwise.  The picture should now be whited out.  If you are using a camera, place something white and something black in front of the camera.  Those who are using a VCR or similar input should find a picture that has this contrast.

Slowly turn the contrast knob counter-clockwise until the black is as black as possible.  Now turn the brightness knob until the white almost fades out.

You should have a good picture now.  Continue to make very small adjustments until you are satisfied with your picture.  Be warned that this may take time and patience.


