The file requester:  When you choose to load or save a file (in whichever format),  the Perfect Vision file requester appears on the screen.  This is a box containing eight lines.

The top line is the Directory line;  here is where you type in your drive letter and/or directory name.  The next line is the Filename line, where you type in the name of the file you want to save or load.  The lower six lines are filled with a list.  If your cursor (represented by the highlighted area) is on the directory line, a list of the current directories will be displayed.  If you are on any of the other lines, a list of the files in this directory that have the same suffix (PCX,TIF, or RAW) as your file will be displayed.

You can move your cursor up and down with the arrow keys.  If your disk has more files on it than can be displayed, you will be able to scroll the six-line list up or down by moving down past the last line or up to the top line.  

Pressing the ENTER key can do two things.  If your cursor is on the top line, the directory displayed on that line will be selected and the file list will be updated.  On any other line, the file name on that line will be chosen and the program will proceed to save or load the named file.

Pressing the F2 key moves the cursor to the top of the file list, but keeps the directories displayed.  This allows you to press ENTER on the directory you want, as if you had typed it into the directory line and pressed ENTER there.

Pressing the ESCAPE key lets you leave the file requester mode without doing anything.

It is not necessary for you to type in the filename extension;  the program will add it automatically.


Preferences:  The file on your disk called "PVPREF.TXT" is a data file that contains a record of your current settings (which video mode, which printer port, etc.).  This file is updated automatically and loaded every time you run your Perfect Vision software.  This is purely for convieniance.


Explanations of the various key functions are at your fingertips with the F1 key, which is the help key for this program.


If you are in a mode with 16 or more color registers available, remember that the menus and lists use color register 15 when they are displayed.  Be careful about setting register 15 to the same color as register 0, as this will make it impossible to read anything.

Appendix A: Video Modes


Perfect Vision supports a total of 9 video modes on 5 different video adapters.  These include the Hercules, CGA, EGA, MCGA, and the VGA.  Each have their advantages and disadvantages.  Usually, the higher the resolution the better the picture, but at the same time it takes more time to update the screen due to the sheer number of pixels processed.

The CGA mode 4 has two palettes of colors to choose from.  The CGA mode 5 has 4 colors but on the original IBM CGA card with composite video output the color was suppressed to produce four gray scales.  Your particular CGA card may or may not do this.  Lastly, the CGA mode 6 has two colors (black and white).  Perfect Vision supports two pixel dithering to effectively give you three gray scales.

The Hercules compatible monochrome card only supports black and white images.  Perfect Vision supports up to 4 pixel dithering which gives you the appearance of having 5 gray scales.

The EGA was the next major improvement to the graphic capabilities of the IBM PC.  Modes 13 and 14 both have 16 colors with 4 gray scales to choose from.  You may have to turn up the brightness of your monitor to see the next to lowest gray scale.  Mode 16 gives you 16 colors from a palette of 64 to choose from.  You can choose up to 4 pixel dithering to give you the appearance of 13 gray scales.

The VGA was announced with the introduction of the PS/2 computers.  It gives you the two new graphic modes 18 and 19.  Mode 19 is the source of all the recent hullabaloo.  It gives you the ability to show 256 colors from a palette of 262,144 with an analog RGB monitor.  Mode 18 has the highest resolution at 640x480 but only allows you to show 16 colors out of the 256K palette.

Finally, something peculiar to the PS/2 Model 30 is the MCGA which is a subset of the other video modes.  It supports all the CGA modes and the VGA mode 19.

