Appendix B: Dithering


Dithering is a sneaky way of using the display to present what appears to be more colors or shades than the display actually supports.  Let's examine the theory behind this.

Images are represented on the display by small dots called "pixels".  Pixels are arranged in rows and columns; the number of   rows and columns depends on your display's resolution.  Each pixel can be one of the colors your display can show, or black (which most people treat as just another color).

Most displays have a high enough resolution so that individual pixels are hard to see, and this is the secret of dithering.  Because pixels are so small and close together, a black pixel placed next to a white pixel looks like one gray pixel.  When placed in the middle of a large picture that fills the display, pairs of such dots can be used to make colors or shades that are blendings of the basic shades produced by the display.

Now, the reason most dithering is made with two pixels side by side is simply this; the function of almost all video screens is such that pixels are more tightly packed side-to-side than they are top-to-bottom.  This means that pixels beside each other blend more easily.

Perfect Vision supports 4-pixel dithering (four pixels in a square) on some video adapters, and of course 2-pixel dithering.  
Since dithering techniques produce a blockier picture, you have to make some tough decisions about what graphic and dithering modes to use based on your video card and your application.  For instance, when digitizing a black-and-white drawing for use in a desktop publishing program, you may wish to use no dithering for the highest resolution possible.  If, however, you wished to make 
a "slideshow" of human faces, you might want to use 4-pixel dithering to get as much depth and texture into the picture as possible.



Appendix C: Printer Ports


When you turn your computer on, it searches for the number of printer ports installed in your computer.  The computer can recognize up to three printer ports (if they are installed).  The computer follows a priority for these ports and designates them as LPT1, LPT2, and LPT3.

Some video adapter boards come with a parallel port included.  Some IBM compatibles come with a parallel port already installed.  Also, I/O boards are available with parallel ports on them.  All of these ports can be configured for one designation or another, but if you have only one parallel port, it will always be seen by the computer as LPT1.

The Perfect Vision software allows you to choose which printer port to use with a selection on the main menu screen.  It does not do this automatically, so if at first you cannot get input from your Perfect Vision, try changing the active port.  Do not automatically assume that if you have two ports they will be LPT1 and LPT2.  Different settings come on different boards.



Appendix D: Pallette Registers


Some video adapter boards come with a predefined set of colors (or gray scales), but most allow a set of color "registers" to be  filled with a color from a larger set called a "pallette".  For example, mode 16 (on EGA and VGA cards) allows for 16 color registers to be filled with colors from a pallette of 64 colors.

The reason that the Perfect Vision software allows you to load PC  Paintbrush files when you cannot edit them is that you also load the particular color register combination used for that picture.  This is useful when capturing sequences of frames for animation purposes, or when you are capturing pictures that you want to merge (using a paint program).



Appendix E: RAW Disk Format


Perfect Vision saves data in a RAW format (really no format at all).  This is an almost straight dump of screen data to a file.  Pixels are saved left-to-right, top-to-bottom in a format of two pixels per byte.  Since pixels coming from the Perfect Vision are always in 16 grey-scales, any pixel can be represented by four bits.  A byte contains 8 bits, so we can put two pixels in a byte.  This method of saving data is definitely not plane-by-plane.

In all 32,000 bytes are saved for each non-interlaced screen, and 64,000 bytes are saved for an interlaced picture.

Because the IBM and Amiga versions of Perfect Vision are really just the same device,  we were able to make the RAW format completely interchangable.  This means that the Perfect Vision software on the Amiga and the PCs can share data just by sending the RAW files through modems.

Also, for our customers who want to use their Perfect Vision on both machines, we offer software kits for a reasonable price.



Appendix F: Color


Perfect Vision was originally developed for the Commodore Amiga computer.  However, from the beginning it was designed so that it 
would be usable by almost any computer with the proper cabling and software.  This is why it is an external box and not a board and why it has its own power supply.

Perfect Vision for the Amiga is capable of doing color pictures using three color filters and a 3-pass process.  The IBM version,  however, being a totally different beast, does not support color in this, first, version.

Color filters are provided for this product not because we don't care to take them out, but because we are commited to providing the IBM user with full color support in a future version of the Perfect Vision-IBM software.  This update will be available for less than $10.00 (perhaps even free) to all registered owners, and is expected in the Fall of 1988.  Just a reminder, then, to send in your registration card.  This is the only way we can be sure to get you all of the information and upgrades available.

When this update becomes available, it will also support our new product, the Perfect Vision Color Splitter.  This box will allow you to grab color pictures from a color camera or freeze-framed VCR. The 9-pin connector on the back of your Perfect Vision is for use with the Color Splitter; the connections will allow software control of the color seperation process.


